[src:webgpu-api/api-gpubuffer] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpubuffer] The **`GPUBuffer`** interface of the WebGPU API represents a block of memory that can be used to store raw data to use in GPU operations.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpubuffer] A `GPUBuffer` object instance is created using the `GPUDevice.createBuffer()` method.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpubuffer] A string providing a label that can be used to identify the object, for example in `GPUError` messages or console warnings.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpubuffer] An enumerated value representing the mapped state of the `GPUBuffer`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpubuffer] A number representing the length of the `GPUBuffer`'s memory allocation, in bytes.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpubuffer] The bitwise flags representing the allowed usages of the `GPUBuffer`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpubuffer] Returns an `ArrayBuffer` containing the mapped contents of the `GPUBuffer` in the specified range.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpubuffer] Maps the specified range of the `GPUBuffer`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpubuffer] Returns a `Promise` that resolves when the `GPUBuffer`'s content is ready to be accessed with `GPUBuffer.getMappedRange()`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpubuffer] Unmaps the mapped range of the `GPUBuffer`, making its contents available for use by the GPU again.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpubuffer] In our basic compute demo, we create an output buffer to read GPU calculations to, and a staging buffer to be mapped for JavaScript access.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] The **`GPUDevice`** interface of the WebGPU API represents a logical GPU device.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] This is the main interface through which the majority of WebGPU functionality is accessed.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] A `GPUDevice` object is requested using the `GPUAdapter.requestDevice()` method.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] A `GPUAdapterInfo` object containing identifying information about the device's originating adapter.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] A `GPUSupportedFeatures` object that describes additional functionality supported by the device.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] A `GPUSupportedLimits` object that describes the limits supported by the device.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Contains a `Promise` that remains pending throughout the device's lifetime and resolves with a `GPUDeviceLostInfo` object when the device is lost.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Returns the primary `GPUQueue` for the device.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUBindGroup` based on a `GPUBindGroupLayout` that defines a set of resources to be bound together in a group and how those resources are used in shader stages.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUBindGroupLayout` that defines the structure and purpose of related GPU resources such as buffers that will be used in a pipeline, and is used as a template when creating `GPUBindGroup`s.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUBuffer` in which to store raw data to use in GPU operations.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUCommandEncoder`, which is used to encode commands to be issued to the GPU.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUComputePipeline` that can control the compute shader stage and be used in a `GPUComputePassEncoder`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a `GPUComputePipeline`, which can control the compute shader stage and be used in a `GPUComputePassEncoder`, once the pipeline can be used without any stalling.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUPipelineLayout` that defines the `GPUBindGroupLayout`s used by a pipeline.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] `GPUBindGroup`s used with the pipeline during command encoding must have compatible `GPUBindGroupLayout`s.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUQuerySet` that can be used to record the results of queries on passes, such as occlusion or timestamp queries.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPURenderBundleEncoder` that can be used to pre-record bundles of commands.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] These can be reused in `GPURenderPassEncoder`s via the `executeBundles()` method, as many times as required.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPURenderPipeline` that can control the vertex and fragment shader stages and be used in a `GPURenderPassEncoder` or `GPURenderBundleEncoder`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a `GPURenderPipeline`, which can control the vertex and fragment shader stages and be used in a `GPURenderPassEncoder` or `GPURenderBundleEncoder`, once the pipeline can be used without any stalling.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUSampler`, which controls how shaders transform and filter texture resource data.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUShaderModule` from a string of WGSL source code.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUTexture` in which to store texture data to use in GPU rendering operations.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Destroys the device, preventing further operations on it.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Takes an `HTMLVideoElement` as an input and returns a `GPUExternalTexture` wrapper object containing a snapshot of the video that can be used in GPU rendering operations.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Pops an existing GPU error scope from the error scope stack and returns a `Promise` that resolves to an object (`GPUInternalError`, `GPUOutOfMemoryError`, or `GPUValidationError`) describing the first error captured in the scope, or `null` if no error occurred.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Pushes a new GPU error scope onto the device's error scope stack, allowing you to capture errors of a particular type.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Fired when an error is thrown that has not been observed by a GPU error scope, to provide a way to report unexpected errors.
[src:webgpu-api/api-gpudevice] Known error cases should be handled using `pushErrorScope()` and `popErrorScope()`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The **WebGPU API** enables web developers to use the underlying system's GPU (Graphics Processing Unit) to carry out high-performance computations and draw complex images that can be rendered in the browser.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] WebGPU is the successor to WebGL, providing better compatibility with modern GPUs, support for general-purpose GPU computations, faster operations, and access to more advanced GPU features.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] It is fair to say that WebGL revolutionized the web in terms of graphical capabilities after it first appeared around 2011.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] WebGL is a JavaScript port of the OpenGL ES 2.0 graphics library, allowing web pages to pass rendering computations directly to the device's GPU to be processed at very high speeds, and render the result inside a `<canvas>` element.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] WebGL and the GLSL language used to write WebGL shader code are complex, so several WebGL libraries have been created to make WebGL apps easier to write: Popular examples include Three.js, Babylon.js, and PlayCanvas.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Developers have used these tools to build immersive web-based 3D games, music videos, training and modeling tools, VR and AR experiences, and more.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] WebGPU addresses these issues, providing an updated general-purpose architecture compatible with modern GPU APIs, which feels more "webby".
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] It supports graphic rendering, but also has first-class support for GPGPU computations.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Rendering of individual objects is significantly cheaper on the CPU side, and it supports modern GPU rendering features such as compute-based particles and post-processing filters like color effects, sharpening, and depth-of-field simulation.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] In addition, it can handle expensive computations such as culling and skinned model transformation directly on the GPU.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] There are several layers of abstraction between a device GPU and a web browser running the WebGPU API.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] A logical device — represented by a `GPUDevice` object instance — is the basis from which a web app accesses all WebGPU functionality.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] You access an adapter via the `GPU.requestAdapter()` method.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] This method accepts an optional settings object allowing you to request, for example, a compatibility mode, high-performance, or low-energy adapter.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] If this is not included, the device will provide access to the default adapter, which is good enough for most purposes.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] A device can be requested via `GPUAdapter.requestDevice()`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] This method also accepts an options object (referred to as a descriptor), which can be used to specify the exact features and limits you want the logical device to have.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] If this is not included, the supplied device will have a reasonable general-purpose spec that is good enough for most purposes.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] By default, a `GPUAdapter` supports all core WebGPU features and limits, which allows applications to support devices with modern platform graphics APIs.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] It is possible to opt WebGPU into "compatibility mode", which specifies that the `GPUAdapter` will support a restricted subset of the WebGPU API capable of running in older graphics APIs such as OpenGL ES 3.1 and Direct3D 11.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The exact restrictions of compatibility mode are detailed at WebGPU Compatibility Mode.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Restricted applications are still valid WebGPU core applications due to supporting a subset of core WebGPU, and will therefore run on all browsers that support core WebGPU, even if they don't explicitly support compatibility mode.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] A `GPUAdapter` or `GPUDevice` that supports core WebGPU will have the `core-features-and-limits` feature available (see `GPUSupportedFeatures`).
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] See also Using compatibility mode only if necessary.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] A pipeline is a logical structure containing programmable stages that are completed to get your program's work done.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The shaders mentioned above are sets of instructions processed by the GPU.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] WebGPU shaders are written in a low-level Rust-like language called WebGPU Shading Language (WGSL).
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Get and configure the canvas context: Get the `webgpu` context of a `<canvas>` element and configure it to receive information on what graphics to render from your GPU logical device.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] This step is not necessary if your app has no graphical output, such as one that only uses compute pipelines.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Create resources containing your data: The data that you want processed by your pipelines needs to be stored in GPU buffers or textures to be accessed by your app.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Create pipelines: Define pipeline descriptors that describe the desired pipelines in detail, including the required data structure, bindings, shaders, and resource layouts, then create pipelines from them.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Our basic demos only contain a single pipeline, but non-trivial apps will usually contain multiple pipelines for different purposes.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Create a pass encoder object on which compute/render commands are issued.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Run commands to specify which pipelines to use, what buffer(s) to get the required data from, how many drawing operations to run (in the case of render pipelines), etc.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Finalize the command list and encapsulate it in a command buffer.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Submit the command buffer to the GPU via the logical device's command queue.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] In the sections below, we will examine a basic render pipeline demo, to allow you to explore what it requires.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Later on, we'll also examine a basic compute pipeline example, looking at how it differs from the render pipeline.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] In our basic render demo we give a `<canvas>` element a solid blue background and draw a triangle onto it.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The vertex shader stage (`@vertex` block) accepts a chunk of data containing a position and a color, positions the vertex according to the given position, interpolates the color, then passes the data along to the fragment shader stage.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The fragment shader stage (`@fragment` block) accepts the data from the vertex shader stage and colors the vertex according to the given color.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] To make your shader code available to WebGPU, you have to put it inside a `GPUShaderModule` via a `GPUDevice.createShaderModule()` call, passing your shader code as a property inside a descriptor object.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] In a render pipeline, we need to specify somewhere to render the graphics to.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] In this case we are getting a reference to an onscreen `<canvas>` element then calling `HTMLCanvasElement.getContext()` with a parameter of `webgpu` to return its GPU context (a `GPUCanvasContext` instance).
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] From there, we configure the context with a call to `GPUCanvasContext.configure()`, passing it an options object containing the `GPUDevice` that the rendering information will come from, the format the textures will have, and the alpha mode to use when rendering semi-transparent textures.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Next we will provide our WebGPU program with our data, in a form it can use.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Our data is initially provided in a `Float32Array`, which contains 8 data points for each triangle vertex — X, Y, Z, W for position, and R, G, B, A for color.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We need to get our data into a `GPUBuffer`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Behind the scenes, this type of buffer is stored in memory very tightly integrated with the GPU's cores to allow for the desired high performance processing.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] As a side effect, this memory can't be accessed by processes running on the host system, like the browser.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The `GPUBuffer` is created via a call to `GPUDevice.createBuffer()`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We give it a size equal to the length of the `vertices` array so it can contain all the data, and `VERTEX` and `COPY_DST` usage flags to indicate that the buffer will be used as a vertex buffer and the destination of copy operations.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We could handle getting our data into the `GPUBuffer` using a mapping operation, like we use in the compute pipeline example to read data from the GPU back to JavaScript.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] However, in this case we are going to use the handy `GPUQueue.writeBuffer()` convenience method, which takes as its parameters the buffer to write to, the data source to write from, an offset value for each, and the size of data to write (we've specified the whole length of the array).
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The browser then works out the most efficient way to handle writing the data.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Now we've got our data into a buffer, the next part of the setup is to actually create our pipeline, ready to be used for rendering.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] First of all, we create an object that describes the required layout of our vertex data.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] This perfectly describes what we saw earlier on in our `vertices` array and vertex shader stage — each vertex has position and color data.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Both are formatted in `float32x4` format (which maps to the WGSL `vec4<f32>` type), and the color data starts at an offset of 16 bytes into each vertex.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] `arrayStride` specifies the stride, meaning the number of bytes making up each vertex, and `stepMode` specifies that the data should be fetched per-vertex.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Next, we create a descriptor object that specifies the configuration of our render pipeline stages.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] For both the shader stages, we specify the `GPUShaderModule` that the relevant code can be found in (`shaderModule`), and the name of the function that acts as the entry point for each stage.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] In addition, in the case of the vertex shader stage we provide our `vertexBuffers` object to provide the expected state of our vertex data.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] And in the case of our fragment shader stage, we provide an array of color target states that indicate the specified rendering format (this matches the format specified in our canvas context config earlier).
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We also specify a `primitive` object, which in this case just states the type of primitive we will be drawing, and a `layout` of `auto`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The `layout` property defines the layout (structure, purpose, and type) of all the GPU resources (buffers, textures, etc.) used during the execution of the pipeline.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] In more complex apps, this would take the form of a `GPUPipelineLayout` object, created using `GPUDevice.createPipelineLayout()` (you can see an example in our Basic compute pipeline), which allows the GPU to figure out how to run the pipeline most efficiently ahead of time.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] However, we are specifying the `auto` value, which will cause the pipeline to generate an implicit bind group layout based on any bindings defined in the shader code.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Finally, we can create a `GPURenderPipeline` based on our `pipelineDescriptor` object, by passing it in as a parameter to a `GPUDevice.createRenderPipeline()` method call.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Now that all the setup is done, we can actually run a rendering pass and draw something onto our `<canvas>`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] To encode any commands to be later issued to the GPU, you need to create a `GPUCommandEncoder` instance, which is done using a `GPUDevice.createCommandEncoder()` call.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Next up we start the rendering pass running by creating a `GPURenderPassEncoder` instance with a `GPUCommandEncoder.beginRenderPass()` call.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] This method takes a descriptor object as a parameter, the only mandatory property of which is a `colorAttachments` array.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] That the view should be "cleared" to a specified color once loaded and before any drawing takes place.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] This is what causes the blue background behind the triangle.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] That the value of the current rendering pass should be stored for this color attachment.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] `GPURenderPassEncoder.setVertexBuffer()` is called with our `vertexBuffer` object as a parameter to act as the data source to pass to the pipeline to render.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The first parameter is the slot to set the vertex buffer for, and is a reference to the index of the element in the `vertexBuffers` array which describes this buffer's layout.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] `GPURenderPassEncoder.draw()` sets the drawing in motion.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] There is data for three vertices inside our `vertexBuffer`, so we set a vertex count value of `3` to draw them all.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] To finish encoding the sequence of commands and issue them to the GPU, three more steps are needed.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We invoke the `GPUCommandEncoder.finish()` method to complete recording of the issued command sequence and encapsulate it into a `GPUCommandBuffer` object instance.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We submit the `GPUCommandBuffer` to the device's command queue (represented by a `GPUQueue` instance) to be sent to the GPU.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The device's queue is available via the `GPUDevice.queue` property, and an array of `GPUCommandBuffer` instances can be added to the queue via a `GPUQueue.submit()` call.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] In our basic compute demo, we get the GPU to calculate some values, store them in an output buffer, copy the data across to a staging buffer, then map that staging buffer so that the data can be read out to JavaScript and logged to the console.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The app follows a similar structure to the basic rendering demo.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We create a `GPUDevice` reference in the same way as before, and encapsulate our shader code into a `GPUShaderModule` via a `GPUDevice.createShaderModule()` call.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] In this example we create two `GPUBuffer` instances to handle our data, an `output` buffer to write the GPU calculation results to at high speed, and a `stagingBuffer` that we'll copy the `output` contents to, which can be mapped to allow JavaScript to access the values.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] When the pipeline is created, we specify a bind group to use for the pipeline.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] This involves first creating a `GPUBindGroupLayout` (via a call to `GPUDevice.createBindGroupLayout()`) that defines the structure and purpose of GPU resources such as buffers that will be used in this pipeline.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] This layout is used as a template for bind groups to adhere to.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] In this case we give the pipeline access to a single memory buffer, tied to binding slot 0 (this matches the relevant binding number in our shader code — `@binding(0)`), usable in the compute stage of the pipeline, and with the buffer's purpose defined as `storage`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Next we create a `GPUBindGroup` by calling `GPUDevice.createBindGroup()`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We pass this method call a descriptor object that specifies the bind group layout to base this bind group on, and the details of the variable to bind to the slot defined in the layout.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] In this case, we are declaring binding 0, and specifying that the `output` buffer we defined earlier should be bound to it.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] With the above all in place, we can now create a compute pipeline by calling `GPUDevice.createComputePipeline()`, passing it a pipeline descriptor object.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] This works in a similar way to creating a render pipeline.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We describe the compute shader, specifying what module to find the code in and what the entry point is.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We also specify a `layout` for the pipeline, in this case creating a layout based on the `bindGroupLayout` we defined earlier via a `GPUDevice.createPipelineLayout()` call.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] One difference here from the render pipeline layout is that we are not specifying a primitive type, as we are not drawing anything.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Running a compute pass is similar in structure to running a rendering pass, with some different commands.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] For a start, the pass encoder is created using `GPUCommandEncoder.beginComputePass()`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] When issuing the commands, we specify the pipeline to use in the same way as before, using `GPUComputePassEncoder.setPipeline()`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We then however use `GPUComputePassEncoder.setBindGroup()` to specify that we want to use our `bindGroup` to specify the data to use in the calculation, and `GPUComputePassEncoder.dispatchWorkgroups()` to specify the number of GPU workgroups to use to run the calculations.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We then signal the end of the render pass command list using `GPURenderPassEncoder.end()`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Before submitting the encoded commands to the GPU for execution using `GPUQueue.submit()`, we copy the contents of the `output` buffer to the `stagingBuffer` buffer using `GPUCommandEncoder.copyBufferToBuffer()`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Once the output data is available in the `stagingBuffer`, we use the `GPUBuffer.mapAsync()` method to map the data to intermediate memory, grab a reference to the mapped range using `GPUBuffer.getMappedRange()`, copy the data into JavaScript, and then log it to the console.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We also unmap the `stagingBuffer` once we are finished with it.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] WebGPU calls are validated asynchronously in the GPU process.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] If errors are found, the problem call is marked as invalid on the GPU side.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] If another call is made that relies on the return value of an invalidated call, that object will also be marked as invalid, and so on.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] For this reason, errors in WebGPU are referred to as "contagious".
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Each `GPUDevice` instance maintains its own error scope stack.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] This stack is initially empty, but you can start pushing an error scope to the stack by invoking `GPUDevice.pushErrorScope()` to capture errors of a particular type.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Once you are done capturing errors, you can end capture by invoking `GPUDevice.popErrorScope()`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] This pops the scope from the stack and returns a `Promise` that resolves to an object (`GPUInternalError`, `GPUOutOfMemoryError`, or `GPUValidationError`) describing the first error captured in the scope, or `null` if no errors were captured.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] We have attempted to provide useful information to help you understand why errors are occurring in your WebGPU code in "Validation" sections where appropriate, which list criteria to meet to avoid errors.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] See for example the `GPUDevice.createBindGroup()` Validation section.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] You can find more information about WebGPU error handling in the explainer — see Object validity and destroyed-ness and Errors.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] WebGPU Error Handling best practices provides useful real-world examples and advice.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The entry point for the API — returns the `GPU` object for the current context.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] It can be used to return a `GPUAdapter`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] From this you can request a `GPUDevice`, adapter info, features, and limits.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Contains identifying information about an adapter.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] A setlike object that describes additional functionality supported by a `GPUAdapter` or `GPUDevice`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Describes the limits supported by a `GPUAdapter` or `GPUDevice`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Invoking `getContext()` with the `"webgpu"` `contextType` returns a `GPUCanvasContext` object instance, which can then be configured with `GPUCanvasContext.configure()`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Represents the WebGPU rendering context of a `<canvas>` element.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Represents a block of memory that can be used to store raw data to use in GPU operations.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] A wrapper object containing an `HTMLVideoElement` snapshot that can be used as a texture in GPU rendering operations.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Controls how shaders transform and filter texture resource data.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] A reference to an internal shader module object, a container for WGSL shader code that can be submitted to the GPU to execution by a pipeline.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] A container used to store 1D, 2D, or 3D arrays of data, such as images, to use in GPU rendering operations.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] A view onto some subset of the texture subresources defined by a particular `GPUTexture`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Based on a `GPUBindGroupLayout`, a `GPUBindGroup` defines a set of resources to be bound together in a group and how those resources are used in shader stages.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Defines the structure and purpose of related GPU resources such as buffers that will be used in a pipeline, and is used as a template when creating `GPUBindGroup`s.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Controls the compute shader stage and can be used in a `GPUComputePassEncoder`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Defines the `GPUBindGroupLayout`s used by a pipeline.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Controls the vertex and fragment shader stages and can be used in a `GPURenderPassEncoder` or `GPURenderBundleEncoder`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Represents a recorded list of GPU commands that can be submitted to a `GPUQueue` for execution.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Represents a command encoder, used to encode commands to be issued to the GPU.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Encodes commands related to controlling the compute shader stage, as issued by a `GPUComputePipeline`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Part of the overall encoding activity of a `GPUCommandEncoder`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] controls execution of encoded commands on the GPU.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] A container for pre-recorded bundles of commands (see `GPURenderBundleEncoder`).
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Encodes commands related to controlling the vertex and fragment shader stages, as issued by a `GPURenderPipeline`.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Used to record the results of queries on passes, such as occlusion or timestamp queries.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] An array of `GPUCompilationMessage` objects, generated by the GPU shader module compiler to help diagnose problems with shader code.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Represents a single informational, warning, or error message generated by the GPU shader module compiler.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Returned when the `GPUDevice.lost` `Promise` resolves, providing information as to why the device was lost.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The base interface for errors surfaced by `GPUDevice.popErrorScope` and the `uncapturederror` event.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] One of the types of errors surfaced by `GPUDevice.popErrorScope` and the `GPUDevice` `uncapturederror` event.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Indicates that an operation failed for a system or implementation-specific reason, even when all validation requirements were satisfied.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Indicates that there was not enough free memory to complete the requested operation.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The value received when a `Promise` returned by a `GPUDevice.createComputePipelineAsync()` or `GPUDevice.createRenderPipelineAsync()` call rejects.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The event object type for the `GPUDevice` `uncapturederror` event.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] Describes an application error indicating that an operation did not pass the WebGPU API's validation constraints.
[src:webgpu-api/api-webgpu-api] The whole API is available only in a secure context.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The main goal of WebAssembly is to facilitate high-performance applications on web pages, but it is also designed to be usable in non-web environments.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] It is an open standard intended to support any language on any operating system, and in practice many of the most popular languages already have at least some level of support.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Announced in 2015 (2015) and first released in March 2017 (2017-03), WebAssembly became a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation on 5 December 2019 and it received the *Programming Languages Software Award* from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The W3C maintains the standard with contributions from Mozilla, Microsoft, Google, Apple, Fastly, Intel, and Red Hat.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The name "WebAssembly" is intended to suggest bringing assembly language programming to the World Wide Web, where it will be executed client-side, by the website-user's computer via the user's web browser.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] To accomplish this, WebAssembly must be much more hardware-independent than a true assembly language.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] WebAssembly was first announced in 2015, and the first demonstration was executing Unity's *Angry Bots* in Firefox, Google Chrome, and Microsoft Edge [Legacy].
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The precursor technologies were asm.js from Mozilla and Google Native Client, and the initial implementation was based on the feature set of asm.js.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] In March 2017, the design of the minimum viable product (MVP) was declared to be finished and the preview phase ended.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] In late September 2017, Safari 11 was released with support.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] In February 2018, the WebAssembly Working Group published three public working drafts for the Core Specification, JavaScript Interface, and Web API.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The MVP was focused on low-level languages such as C and C++, with the intent to add features useful for high-level languages in a future version.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The WebAssembly 2.0 specification was finished in 2022 and became a W3C standard in December 2024.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] It adds many single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) related instructions and a new v128 datatype, with the ability for functions to return multiple values, mass memory initialize/copy instructions, and reference types, which are opaque pointers to objects outside of the linear memory.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] WebAssembly 3.0 was released in September 2025.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] New features include a 64-bit address space, multiple address spaces, exception handling, and garbage collected struct and array types.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Support for garbage collection enables more efficient compiling for high-level languages, but WasmGC from WebAssembly 3.0 lacks the abilities needed by .NET runtime.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] While WebAssembly was initially designed to permit near-native code execution speed in the web browser, it has been considered valuable outside of such, in more generalized contexts.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] A WebAssembly runtime environment is a low-level virtual stack machine, akin to JVM or Flash VM; it can be embedded into any host application, and thus there have been created standalone WebAssembly runtime environments, including Wasmtime , WebAssembly Micro Runtime , Wasmer , WasmEdge and wazero .
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] In November 2017, Mozilla declared support "in all major browsers", after WebAssembly was enabled by default in Edge [Legacy] 16.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] This support also includes mobile web browsers for iOS and Android.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] As of March 2024, 99% of tracked web browsers support WebAssembly (version 1.0), more than for its predecessor asm.js.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] For some extensions, from the 2.0 draft standard, support may be lower, but still more than 90% of web browsers may already support, e.g. the reference types extension.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Non-browser WebAssembly runtimes include Wasmer, Wasmtime, WAMR, WAVM, wasm3, and others.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] These systems execute precompiled Wasm modules and often provide additional APIs for embedding WebAssembly in different environments.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Use cases for wasm outside the browser include plug-in interfaces and lightweight virtualization.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] WebAssembly implementations generally use either ahead-of-time (AOT) or just-in-time (JIT) compiling, though some may also use an interpreter.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] While the first implementations appeared in web browsers, there are now many non-browser implementations for general-purpose use.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Because WebAssembly executables are precompiled, a variety of programming languages can target Wasm.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Compiling is done either through direct output to Wasm or via intermediate virtual machines implemented in Wasm.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] As of 2021, around 40 programming languages support WebAssembly as a compiling target.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Web browsers prevent WebAssembly code from directly manipulating the Document Object Model.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Wasm code must defer to JavaScript for this.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] In an October 2023 survey of developers, less than half of the 303 participants were satisfied with the state of WebAssembly.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] A large majority cited the need for improvement in four areas: § WASI, debugging support, integration with JavaScript and browser APIs, and build tooling.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] All major browsers allow WebAssembly if `Content-Security-Policy` is not specified, or if the value `unsafe-eval` is used, but behave differently otherwise; Chrome *requires* `unsafe-eval`, though a worker thread can be a workaround.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] In June 2018, a security researcher presented the possibility of using WebAssembly to circumvent browser mitigations for Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities once support for threads with shared memory is added.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Due to this concern, WebAssembly developers put the feature on hold.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] However, in order to explore these future language extensions, Google Chrome added experimental support for the WebAssembly thread proposal in October 2018.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] WebAssembly has been criticized for allowing greater ease of hiding the evidence for malware writers, scammers and phishing attackers; WebAssembly is present on the user's machine only in its compiled form, which "[makes malware] detection difficult".
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Speed and the easy ability to conceal in WebAssembly have led to its use in hidden crypto mining within the website visitor's device.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] An April 2021 study from Universität Stuttgart found that since then crypto mining has been marginalized, falling to below 1% of all WebAssembly modules gathered from a wide range of sources, also including the Alexa top 1 million websites.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] As WebAssembly supports only structured control flow, it is amenable toward security verification techniques including symbolic execution.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] In 2019, a group of researchers from the University of Massachusetts Amherst presented a comprehensive analysis of WebAssembly's performance compared to native code.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The paper identified several reasons for this performance difference, including missing optimizations, code generation issues in WebAssembly compilers, and inherent limits of the WebAssembly platform.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] In 2022, it was determined by researchers that a Wasm program runs at about 120% of (or 20% faster than) the speed of a comparable JavaScript program.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Those findings align with the experience of a startup company named "Zaplib", whose founders summarized in a blog that it was shutting down due to lack of performance in WebAssembly.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Their goal had been to significantly increase the performance of existing web apps by incrementally porting them to Rust/Wasm; however, porting a customer's simulator from JavaScript yielded only a 5% improvement in performance.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Benchmarking has revealed several other pain-points for WebAssembly, such as poor performance because of no direct access to the DOM, a problem which is being addressed.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is a simple interface (application binary interface (ABI) and application programming interface (API)) designed by Mozilla, which is intended to be portable to any platform.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] It provides features similar to the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), such as file input/output (I/O) constrained by capability-based security.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] WASI is influenced by CloudABI and Capsicum.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Solomon Hykes, a co-founder of Docker, wrote in 2019, "If WASM+WASI existed in 2008, we wouldn't have needed to create Docker.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] WASI 0.1 provides a few POSIX-like APIs such as file I/O, reading environment variables, and random-number generation, but has very little support for networking.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] WASI 0.2 is redesigned based on the WebAssembly Component Model.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] WASI 0.3 will add support for async functions; the host translates between blocking and async function calls, so an exported function that blocks may be called as an asynchronous function, and vice-versa.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Starting in 0.2, WASI is defined in terms of the component model.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Interfaces in the component model are specified in an IDL called WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types).
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] While core wasm only supports integer and floating-point numbers, interfaces in WIT can express types such as strings, lists, and user-defined record and variant types, and are language-agnostic.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Components cannot access each other's memory, and so interact only via imported and exported functions.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The component model is designed around composition: two components can be composed into a single component when the exports of one component match another's imports, allowing any interface to be virtualized.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Interfaces in WIT are grouped together into a "world".
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] WASI 0.2 defines a CLI world similar to the POSIX-like API of WASI 0.1, and an HTTP proxy world for web servers.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The component model is not currently supported by browsers.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The general standard provides core specifications for the JavaScript API and details on embedding.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Wasm code (binary code, i.e. bytecode) is intended to be run on a portable virtual stack machine (VM).
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The VM is designed to be faster to parse and execute than JavaScript and to have compact code representation.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Any external functionality (like syscalls) that may be expected by Wasm binary code is not stipulated by the standard; instead, the standard specifies how the host environment can provide such an interface via a "module".
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] A Wasm program is designed as a separate module containing collections of various Wasm-defined values and program type definitions.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] These are provided in either binary or textual format (see below) that have a common structure.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Such a module may provide a start function that is executed upon instantiation of a wasm binary.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The list of instruction types includes those for standard memory load/store, numeric, parametric, control flow, and Wasm-specific variables.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The number of opcodes used in the original standard (§ MVP) was a bit fewer than 200 of the 256 possible opcodes.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Subsequent versions of WebAssembly pushed the number of opcodes a bit over 200.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The WebAssembly SIMD proposal (for parallel processing) introduces an alternate opcode prefix (0xfd) for 128-bit wide SIMD instructions; the concatenation of the SIMD prefix, plus an opcode that is valid after the SIMD prefix, forms each SIMD opcode.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] These SIMD opcodes are both portable and intended to map directly to native instruction sets like x86-64 and ARM.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] In contrast, SIMD instructions are not directly supported by Java's JVM or .NET's CIL; however, both do have some APIs for parallel processing, which provide SIMD speedups.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] A newer set of "relaxed SIMD" instructions allow for a limited amount of implementation-defined behavior to improve performance.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] In March 2017, the WebAssembly Community Group reached consensus on the initial ("MVP") binary format, JavaScript API, and reference interpreter.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] It defines a WebAssembly binary format (`.wasm`), which is designed to be used by computers, not humans, and a text format that is human-readable (`.wat`), resembling a cross between S-expressions and traditional assembly languages.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The binary format is straightforward and designed to allow streaming compiling, so compiling can begin before the module is finished downloading, and to allow functions to be compiled in parallel.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] All integer constants are encoded using a space-efficient, variable-length LEB128 encoding.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The WebAssembly text format is more canonically written in a folded format using S-expressions.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] For instructions and expressions, this format is purely syntactic sugar and has no behavioral differences with the linear format.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] A module is implicitly generated by the compiler.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The function is referenced by an entry of the type table in the binary, hence a type section and the `type` emitted by the decompiler.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The compiler and decompiler can be accessed online.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Data in memory is stored in a large, growable array of bytes termed a *linear memory*.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Linear memory is separate from the wasm module's call stack and code and the engine's memory.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] This allows running wasm code in the same process as the JavaScript virtual machine it's embedded in without violating memory safety.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] A module contains a list of global variables separate from linear memory, which may be mutable or immutable.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Functions declare a list of local variables.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] A function's parameters are also local variables.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Instructions operate on a stack of values.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The stack layout is fixed (branches must push and pop the same number of operands), so wasm engines can compile the stack away, producing efficient machine code operations on registers, rather than managing a stack at runtime.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] A stack machine architecture was chosen as it can have higher code density than a register machine.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Unlike typical assembly languages, wasm only uses structured control flow similar to high-level programming languages.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The intentional lack of support for jump instructions makes it simple to validate and compile wasm code in a single pass, and makes it easier to read code disassembled into the text format.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Blocks are delimited with the `block`, `loop`, and `if`/`else` constructs.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Branch instructions contain a label that identifies the depth of a block it is nested in: `br 0` will branch to the block the instruction is contained in, `br 1` will branch to the block that block is contained in, and so on.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Branches to a `block` or `if` jump to the end of the block like a break statement, while branches to a `loop` jump back to the *beginning* of the loop, similar to a continue statement.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] The `br_table` instruction takes an input index and jumps to a target from a list of labels.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] A C-style switch statement can be expressed with a `br_table` inside a series of nested blocks.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Compilers targeting wasm convert unstructured control flow into high-level loops using Emscripten's Relooper algorithm, originally designed to target JavaScript.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Function declarations are listed in a separate section before the section containing the function bodies.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Function pointers are emulated using an index into the global functions table, since code is not inside the linear memory.
[src:webgpu-api/webassembly] Functions can also be imported and exported, providing the foreign function interface to communicate with JavaScript or other embedders.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] WebGL programs consist of control code written in JavaScript, and shader code written in OpenGL ES Shading Language (GLSL ES, sometimes referred to as ESSL), a language similar to C or C++.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] WebGL code is executed on a computer's GPU.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] WebGL is designed and maintained by the non-profit Khronos Group.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] On February 9, 2022, Khronos Group announced WebGL 2.0 support from all major browsers.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] From 2024, a new graphics API, WebGPU, is being developed to supersede WebGL.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] WebGPU provides extended capabilities, a more modern interface, and direct GPU access, which is useful for demanding graphics as well as AI applications.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] WebGL 1.0 is based on OpenGL ES 2.0 and provides an API for 3D graphics.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] It uses the HTML5 canvas element and is accessed using Document Object Model (DOM) interfaces.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] It guarantees the availability of many optional extensions of WebGL 1.0, and exposes new APIs.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Automatic memory management is provided implicitly by JavaScript.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Like OpenGL ES 2.0, WebGL lacks the fixed-function APIs introduced in OpenGL 1.0 and deprecated in OpenGL 3.0.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] This functionality, if required, has to be implemented by the developer using shader code and JavaScript.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Shaders in WebGL are written in GLSL and passed to the WebGL API as text strings.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] The WebGL implementation compiles these strings to GPU code.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] This code is executed for each vertex sent through the API and for each pixel rasterized to the screen.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] WebGL evolved out of the Canvas 3D experiments started by Vladimir Vukićević at Mozilla.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Vukićević first demonstrated a Canvas 3D prototype in 2006.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] By the end of 2007, both Mozilla and Opera had made their own separate implementations.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] In early 2009, the non-profit technology consortium Khronos Group started the WebGL Working Group, with initial participation from Apple, Google, Mozilla, Opera, and others.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Version 1.0 of the WebGL specification was released March 2011.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] An early application of WebGL was Zygote Body.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] In November 2012 Autodesk announced that they ported most of their applications to the cloud running on local WebGL clients.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] These applications included Autodesk Fusion and AutoCAD.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Development of the WebGL 2 specification started in 2013 and finished in January 2017.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] The specification is based on OpenGL ES 3.0.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] First implementations are in Firefox 51, Chrome 56 and Opera 43.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Almost Native Graphics Layer Engine (ANGLE) is an open source graphic engine which implements WebGL 1.0 (2.0 which closely conforms to ES 3.0) and OpenGL ES 2.0 and 3.0 standards.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] It is a default backend for both Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox on Windows platforms and works by translating WebGL and OpenGL calls to available platform-specific APIs.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] WebGL is widely supported by modern browsers.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] However, its availability depends on other factors, too, like whether the GPU supports it.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] The official WebGL website offers a simple test page.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] More detailed information (like what renderer the browser uses, and what extensions are available) can be found at third-party websites.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Some such libraries were ported to JavaScript from other languages.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Examples of libraries that provide high-level features include A-Frame (VR), BabylonJS, PlayCanvas, three.js, OSG.JS, Google’s model-viewer and CopperLicht.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Web3D also made a project called X3DOM to make X3D and VRML content run on WebGL.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] There has been an emergence of 2D and 3D game engines for WebGL, such as Unreal Engine 4 and Unity.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] The Stage3D/Flash-based Away3D high-level library also has a port to WebGL via TypeScript.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] A more light-weight utility library that provides just the vector and matrix math utilities for shaders is sylvester.js.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] It is sometimes used in conjunction with a WebGL specific extension called glUtils.js.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] There are also some 2D libraries built atop WebGL, like Cocos2d-x or Pixi.js, which were implemented this way for performance reasons in a move that parallels what happened with the Starling Framework over Stage3D in the Flash world.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] The WebGL-based 2D libraries fall back to HTML5 canvas when WebGL is not available.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Removing the rendering bottleneck by giving almost direct access to the GPU has exposed performance limitations in the JavaScript implementations.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Some were addressed by asm.js and WebAssembly (similarly, the introduction of Stage3D exposed performance problems within ActionScript, which were addressed by projects like CrossBridge).
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] As with any other graphics API, creating content for WebGL scenes requires using a 3D content creation tool and exporting the scene to a format that is readable by the viewer or helper library.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Desktop 3D authoring software such as Blender, Autodesk Maya or SimLab Composer can be used for this purpose.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] In particular, Blend4Web allows a WebGL scene to be authored entirely in Blender and exported to a browser with a single click, even as a standalone web page.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] There are also some WebGL-specific software such as CopperCube and the online WebGL-based editor Clara.io.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Online platforms such as Sketchfab and Clara.io allow users to directly upload their 3D models and display them using a hosted WebGL viewer.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] Starting from Firefox Version 27, Mozilla has given Firefox built-in WebGL tools that allow the editing of vertices and fragment shaders.
[src:webgpu-api/webgl] A number of other debugging and profiling tools have also emerged.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] In JavaScript, WebGPU can be provided by a web browser or other JavaScript environment like Node.js and Deno.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Rust and C++ can use their respective implementations of the WebGPU specification.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Other languages like Python, Java, and Go can use WebGPU by extending the C language specification.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Google Chrome and Microsoft Edge first released WebGPU support in April 2023.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Safari debuted WebGPU support in June 2025 with Safari 26.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Firefox first released WebGPU in July 2025 with Firefox 141.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] The W3C standard is a candidate recommendation.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] WebGPU enables 3D graphics within an HTML canvas.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] It also has robust support for general-purpose GPU computations.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] WebGPU uses its own shading language called WebGPU Shading Language (WGSL) that was designed to be trivially translatable to SPIR-V, until complaints caused redirection into a more traditional design, similar to other shading languages.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Tint is a Google-made compiler for WGSL.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Naga is a similar project developed for the needs of wgpu-rs.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Both Google Chrome and Firefox support WebGPU and WGSL.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Firefox and Deno use the Rust wgpu library.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Safari follows upstream specifications of both WebGPU and WGSL.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Chrome version 113 enabled initial WebGPU support on Windows devices with Direct3D 12, ChromeOS devices with Vulkan, and macOS with Metal.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] This support for Android was enabled in version 121.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] On June 8, 2016, Google showed "Explicit web graphics API" presentation to the WebGL working group (during the bi-annual face to face meeting).
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] The presentation explored the basic ideas and principles of building a new API to eventually replace WebGL, aka "WebGL Next".
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] On January 24, 2017, Khronos hosted an IP-free meeting dedicated to discussion of "WebGL Next" ideas, collided with WebGL working group meeting in Vancouver.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Google team presented the NXT prototype implementing a new API that could run in Chromium with OpenGL, or standalone with OpenGL and Metal.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] NXT borrowed concepts from all of Vulkan, Direct3D 12, and Metal native APIs.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Apple and Mozilla representatives also showed their prototypes built on Safari and Servo correspondingly, both of which closely replicated the Metal API.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] On February 7, 2017, Apple's WebKit team proposed the creation of the W3C community group to design the API.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] At the same time they announced a technical proof of concept and proposal under the name "WebGPU", based on concepts in Apple's Metal.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] The WebGPU name was later adopted by the community group as a working name for the future standard rather than just Apple's initial proposal.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] The initial proposal has been renamed to "WebMetal" to avoid further confusion.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] The W3C "GPU for the Web" Community Group was launched on February 16, 2017.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] At this time, all of Apple, Google, and Mozilla had experiments in the area, but only Apple's proposal was officially submitted to the "gpuweb-proposals" repository.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] Shortly after, on March 21, 2017, Mozilla submitted a proposal for WebGL Next within Khronos repository, based on the Vulkan design.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] On June 1, 2018, citing "resolution on most-high level issues" in the cross-browser standardization effort, Google's Chrome team announced intent to implement the future WebGPU standard.
[src:webgpu-api/webgpu] On 13 February, 2020, Google unveiled Tint as an alternative to WHLSL textual language proposal to WebGPU API, and the language eventually became the standardized WebGPU Shading Language (WGSL), and Tint became the name of compiler within Dawn, the WebGPU implementation of Chromium.
